<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Bird-Dog">Bird Dog</h3>



<p>The <a href="https://www.mdpi.com/1660-4601/16/19/3509" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">bird dog</a> exercise works postural muscles, specifically the <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537074/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">erector spinae</a> muscles. These primarily work to stabilize the spine, which is necessary for posture and spinal stability.</p>



<p>This exercise additionally works the gluteus, hamstrings, latissimus dorsi, serratus anterior, trapezius, posterior deltoid, and iliopsoas muscles. All these muscles are used daily in activities such as walking, sitting, picking up heavy objects, and lifting objects above your head.&nbsp;</p>



<p>The <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/bird-dog" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">bird dog</a> also helps improve general strength and coordination and may potentially <a href="https://www.mdpi.com/1660-4601/16/19/3509" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">relieve back pain</a>.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe loading="lazy" title="Bird Dogs" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/980261062?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Bird Dog Guide. Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">How To Do</h4>



<ol>
<li>Start in a tabletop position, with your hands and knees on the ground.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Slowly extend your right arm forward and your left leg backward. Keep both limbs parallel to the floor.</li>



<li>Pause briefly and slowly bring your arm and leg back to the starting position.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Repeat on the opposite limbs.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Continue steps 2–4 until goal repetitions are met.&nbsp;</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Tips</h4>



<ul>
<li>Exhale when you extend your arm and leg outward. Inhale when you draw your arm and leg back in.</li>



<li>Maintain a neutral spine. Do this by engaging your core muscles throughout this movement.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Do not rotate your torso during this movement. Keep your hips and shoulders square to the floor to avoid this.</li>
</ul>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Optimal Sets And Reps</h4>



